post_text:
Join us on Wednesday, June 17th at 4:00.
This week's YOU GOT THIS parenting seminar will feature Jackie Skramstad, LCSW. Jackie will be discussing resiliency in our parenting!
Jackie has been working in community mental health for almost 30 years, and has worked for Mind Springs Health since 2002. She is the clinical operations manager with oversight of clinical programs across the 10 county region served by Mind Springs Health. Jackie has been in the mental health field for almost 30 years. During her time with Mind Springs Health she has been involved with training and implementation of DBT programming. She also has expertise in the area of child and family treatment and emergency services. She values service to her community and is a member of Rotary Club. Jackie has a passion for hiking, camping and being outdoors. Mind Springs Health & West Springs Hospital Aspen Education Foundation Aspen School District

post_text:
This weeks YOU GOT THIS Parenting Seminar... We welcome Emily R. Supino!
Emily has a Bachelors in Psychology from the University of Missouri specializing in child development. She received her Masters in Counseling Psychology from the University of Colorado-Denver with a clinical mental health and school counseling focus. Emily was a school counselor in Durango, CO from 2013 to 2016, and started practicing play therapy in a private setting there in 2015 before moving to Aspen and opening her practice. Emily provides client-centered play and talk therapy to children, adolescents, and adults utilizing aspects of synergetic play therapy, mindfulness, and solution-focused therapy. Her work focuses on emotion regulation, attention and impulse control, trauma, attachment, anxiety, and depression. She believes individuals thrive on consistent, caring relationships, thus family coaching is an important component of her services. Aspen Education Foundation Mind Springs Health Aspen School District

post_text:
Meet Erin Cummings...

Erin is the CCR Family Support Specialist for Aspen Family Connections. She moved to Colorado in 2011 and relocated to the Roaring Fork Valley in 2017. Prior to joining AFC, Erin worked in special education, community mental health, and worked with individuals with intellectual and developmental disabilities. Erin has a masters in social work from Colorado State University. She is passionate about travel and enjoying the outdoors. Erin’s quiet demeanor and ability to serve others makes you feel welcomed and loved. Throughout the last weeks, Erin has been working with families, distributing and collecting food for our community! Aspen School District Aspen Education Foundation

post_text: Meet Erin Kinney, M.A. LPC. Erin is a part-time case manager for Aspen Family Connections. However right now her job is far from part time. Erin has been serving the community of Aspen and Snowmass by supporting her clients, families and community for the last few months. She is on the front line of the food distributions connecting with each car as they arrive. Erin has lived in the Roaring Fork Valley since 2014. Prior to working at AFC, Erin worked as a school based therapist, taught parenting classes and provided therapy to children, teens, and adults in a community mental health setting. Her master’s degree is in clinical psychology. Her family includes her husband and two daughters. In her free time, Erin enjoys trail running, mountain and road biking, skiing and hiking. Erin makes a point to know your heart and how you are within in the first 10 seconds of meeting her! Aspen School District Town of Snowmass Village

post_text: Meet our director of Aspen Family Connections... Katherine Sand. She is bright, she is clever, she is funny and she cares deeply for our community. Since COVID-19 restrictions have begun, Katherine and the AFC team have dedicated their work to serving food, receiving food and providing emotional and economic support to our Pitkin County families and beyond. Katherine finds her work as director of Aspen Family Connections to be the most powerful and rewarding of her professional career. Since moving to Aspen in 2001, she has been involved with a number of wonderful organizations in the community, including Theatre Aspen and the Aspen Thrift Shop, for which she is proud to still serve as a Board member and chair of the Grants Committee. Katherine is married to Scott and they have twin sons, Alex and Jeremy, who are finishing out their junior year at Aspen High School. We are so thankful for Katherine and her leadership to the AFC team. You can find her weekly updates Aspen Education Foundation in their new content series. Aspen School District

Join YouthZone for a moderated conversation for parents and caregivers about the realities of parent-child dynamics in this time of social distancing and sheltering in place. Parents are now dealing with the new normal of having to work from home while parenting full time. This quarantine can be extra challenging for multi-generational families, families living in close quarters and multi-family homes. Our panel of experts will answer your questions, offer insights and discuss strategies for maintaining peace in the time of COVID-19. You can do this!

There’s no quit in quarantine!

Spanish translation will be available

AEF CONTENT SERIES | What can my child do with all this free time?!
With the school day shortened, parks closed, and all extra-curricular activities on hold, our families are searching to fill the days in a meaningful way. We are fortunate to live in a beautiful mountain town. Getting outside to bike, walk, scooter, hike – all at the proper 6 feet social distance – will definitely help with the cabin fever. For that time inside, we reached out to our Pitkin Library for help – we picked our favorite suggestions from the Aspen Youth Center – and scoured the internet for more. We hope you will enjoy!

post_text: Great advice from Rachel Simmons about how to support your teens and school work. Choose to be their parent first and journey this with them.
shared_text:
Rachel Simmons
March 18 at 6:26 PM ·

How are parents supposed to supervise teens while they're attending school from home? ⁣
⁣
In two decades of work with adolescents, I've learned that "you don't trust me" is a huge point of contention between parents. I spoke to Good Morning America this morning (from my house! live! in sweatpants!) about how to strike the balance between giving teens their space and supervising their work. ⁣
⁣
Huge thanks to the teens who DM'd with their advice. And if you think I left anything out, let me know—I'm sure there will be many more conversations to come.

You can't stop what you don't know! Officer Jermaine Galloway researches drug trends and the drug culture of a community. He will identify local pop culture trends that promote alcohol and drug use. To help prevent youth substance use, we MUST know what's going on in our community. This workshop is intended for educators, prevention providers, coalition members, school administrators, counselors, law enforcement, probation officers, parents, and any interested community member.
